Eclipse build number: I200405210800
CDT build number: 200405290301

Test Case:
1. Launch eclipse.
2. Create a managed make C++ project. Create a file under the project and add 
the following code to it:

int 
main(int argc, char **argv) { 
    cout << "Starting test case!\n"; 

    B::SD_01* p; 

    p = new B::SD_01();     // ** (A) ** 

    p->goBubbleSort(); 


    for (int i = 0; i < 10; ++i) {     
        cout << "Printing number " << i << "\n"; 
    } 

    cout << "Stopping test case!\n";     // ** (B) ** 
} 

3. Add breakpoints on lines A and B above. Then start the debugger for this 
project. 
4. Hit F5 twice to step into the breakpoints. 
It gives an error that "Source not found -- cannot find cmath" after hitting 
F5 second time.I don't include any such file (cmath) in the project. The 
following four exceptions are also thrown in the log file:

Created an attachment (id=11364)
Screenshot of the debug error got on stepping into the breakpoint.

This is not an error. You are trying to step into the "new" operator. This code 
id not a part of your project. That is the reason why debugger can't find the 
source file. As you can see in the Debug view, the source file that contains 
the "new" operator is "\usr\include\c++\3.3.1\cmath". So this behavior is 
expected.
I will investigate the exceptions, looks like a bug in the Eclipse framework.

Marking this as "WORKSFORME". For NPE see 
https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=68413.
